1. If you try to convert the cycle count data to tidy format (which you don't have to do for this assignment, because it's hard), what is one obstacle you will encounter?

bike_data %>%
    group_by(Counter_Spot) %>%
    summarise(n())

## 10 East_Coast_Road Cyclists                      731

Tidydata consists of unique observations only. We can tell from the table above that, for some streets, the 3 initial datasets of different years each had different naming (e.g. Curran St total, Curran Street Total, Curran Street Total Cyclists), and this violates the tidyverse's unique observation rule. It is hard to merge them together because although humans can easily detect such naming errors, it is not the case for the computers. Merge process would require laborious human interference of renaming each overlapping Counter_Spot and creating new variable for the new names (as we did in Lab 2).

3. Draw suitable graphs to display how the number of cyclists varies over time, over season, over day of the week, and with rain

which_season = function(month) {
    if (month %in% c("Dec", "Jan", "Feb")){
        season = "Summer"
    } else if (month %in% c("Mar", "Apr", "May")){
        season = "Fall"
    } else if (month %in% c("Jun", "Jul", "Aug")){
        season = "Winter"
    } else if (month %in% c("Sep", "Oct", "Nov")){
        season = "Spring"
    }
    season
}   



bike_rain_day <- bike_rain_day %>% 
    mutate(Dow=factor(weekdays(Date, abbreviate=TRUE), c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun"))) %>%
    mutate(Season=factor(map(months(bike_rain_day$Date, abbreviate = TRUE), which_season), c("Summer", "Fall", "Winter", "Spring")))

# Plot
bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`bike_count/day`)) + geom_line() + geom_smooth() + labs(title = 'Auckland Total Bike Counts Over Time')
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

There is a clear seasonal effect on the bike counts. As seen from the curves of the blue smooth line, bike counts decrease as winter gets closer (around Jun/Jul), then increases as summer approaches (Dec/Jan).

bike_rain_day <- bike_rain_day %>%
    mutate(Year=format(Date, "%Y")) 
# Over dow
bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`bike_count/day`, col=Dow)) + geom_line() + labs(title = 'Bike Counts Over Day')

bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`bike_count/day`, col=Dow)) + geom_smooth(method="gam") + labs(title = 'Smoothed Bike Counts Over Day')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

There seems to be a sign of two clumpings of weekdays and weekends, but it is not strong. It could be argued that in general there were less bikes counted in the weekends, especially near the end of the dataset.

bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`bike_count/day`, col=Year))+ labs(title = 'Smoothed Bike Counts Over Year') + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

It seems like 2016 had significantly less bike counts compared to other years. 2017 and 2018 don't seem to differ much in terms of total counted number of bikes.

bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`rain_mm/day`)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.33) + labs(title = "Rain Over Time")

Rain was not present in majority of the days.

bike_rain_day <- bike_rain_day %>%
    mutate(Rain_Present=`rain_mm/day`>0)

bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`bike_count/day`)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~Rain_Present) + geom_smooth(method = "gam") + labs(title = "Bike Counts On Rain Present / or Not")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

It seems clear that, in general, there are less bikes observed when there's any rain present. It's also reasonable to assume quadratic effect on the rain_mm/day because people may still choose to ride bikes when there's small amount of rain present, but certainly not when there's heavy rain.

rain_amount = function(rain) {
    if (rain == 0){
        amount = "None"
    } else if (rain > 0 & rain <= 15){
        amount = "Some"
    } else{
        amount = "Moderate/Heavy"
    }
    amount
}   

bike_rain_day <- bike_rain_day %>% 
    mutate(Rain_Amount=factor(map(bike_rain_day$`rain_mm/day`, rain_amount), c("None", "Some", "Moderate/Heavy")))

bike_rain_day %>% ggplot(aes(x=Date, y=`bike_count/day`)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~Rain_Amount) + geom_smooth(method = "gam") + labs(title = "Bike Counts On Rain Amount")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

The number of bike counts goes down a lot when there's moderate/heavy rain (>15mm/day) present. Quadratic effect of rain_mm/day seems to be present.

4. Fit a regression model to predict the number of cyclists from year, season, day of the week, and rain.

We can tell from the previous question that variables (Dow, Season, rain_mm/day, rain_mm/day^2, Year, Rain_Present) all have significant effect on the number of bikes counted in Auckland.

bike_reg = lm(`bike_count/day` ~ Dow + Season + poly(`rain_mm/day`, 2, raw = TRUE) + Year + Rain_Present, data=bike_rain_day)

5. Based on your graphs and model, does rain have a big impact on the number of people cycling in Auckland?

Yes, rain seems to have a quite significant impact on the number of people cycling in Auckland. The graphs in Question 3 graphically shows that the number of bikes decrase as rain accumulates. The fit is reasonably accurate for prediction (R-Squared = 0.7) and the rain variables fitted in the linear regression in Question 4 all pass the anova test with high significance. Those variables' coefficients called by summary() indicates that rain has negative impact on the number of bike counts (Rain_PresentTRUE = -1247.7, poly(rain_mm/day, 2, raw = TRUE)1 = -197.88). Interestingly, the coefficient poly(rain_mm/day, 2, raw = TRUE)2 is a positive value, but it is very small (=1.3) compared to the value of poly(rain_mm/day, 2, raw = TRUE)1 which means that it has taken the small positive value only for the better fit of the regression, and overall, the amount of rain has significant negative impact. This is provable by the decrease in R-squared value when the second polynomial term is removed from the fit.

bike_reg_no_poly = lm(`bike_count/day` ~ Dow + Season + `rain_mm/day` + Year + Rain_Present, data=bike_rain_day)

cat("R-Squared with Polynomial Term:", summary(bike_reg)$r.squared, "\n")
## R-Squared with Polynomial Term: 0.7041155
cat("R-Squared without Polynomial Term:", summary(bike_reg_no_poly)$r.squared)
## R-Squared without Polynomial Term: 0.6635896
